  "text": "The presence of P. vulgaris and Proteus sp. strains in microbial consortia capable of pesticide degradation was detected in highly contaminated soils in Colombia [CITATION_1] . From soil samples exposed to different kinds of waste (including hazardous ones), a microbial consortium was isolated composed of ten strains, including P. vulgaris and Proteus sp. The cons o r t i u m w a s a b l e t o d e g r a d e t w o w i d e l y u s e d organophosphatic pesticides, chlorpyrifos and methyl parathion, both in culture medium and in soil. A similar bacterial consortium was found in highly contaminated soil samples from Moravia, Medellin, an area that was used as a garbage dump from 1974 to 1982 [CITATION_2] . The consortium was able to degrade methyl parathion and p-nitrophenol as the only source of carbon and to decrease their toxicity in the medium and in soil at different depths.",
